---
import BaseLayout from "../../../layouts/BaseLayout.astro";
const base = import.meta.env.BASE_URL.endsWith("/")
  ? import.meta.env.BASE_URL
  : `${import.meta.env.BASE_URL}/`;
---

<BaseLayout title="Skills Learning" description="Learning notes on agent skills inside Agentic Coding.">
  <section class="docs-page">
    <div class="docs-topline">
      <p class="eyebrow">Agentic Coding / Skills</p>
      <a class="button-link outline" href={`${base}agentic-coding/skills/verified/`}>Verified Skills</a>
    </div>

    <div class="docs-layout">
      <article class="docs-main">
        <header class="docs-header">
          <h1>Skills Learning</h1>
          <p>
            My notes on what agent skills are, why they matter, and how I test them inside real
            agentic coding workflows.
          </p>
        </header>

        <section class="docs-section" id="recommended-reading">
          <h2>Recommended Reading</h2>
          <div class="reference-grid">
            <a class="reference-card" href="https://agentskills.io/home#why-agent-skills">
              <span class="reference-source">Agent Skills</span>
              <strong>Agent Skills Overview</strong>
              <p>
                The open Agent Skills standard, originally developed by Anthropic and supported
                by Codex, for packaging agent instructions, resources, and workflows.
              </p>
              <span class="reference-domain">agentskills.io</span>
            </a>
          </div>
        </section>

        <section class="docs-section" id="my-takeaway">
          <h2>My Takeaway</h2>
          <h3>Notes from the Agent Skills docs</h3>
          <h4>Best practices</h4>
          <p>
            Writing a skill is already a small task. Codex has a built-in
            <a href="https://developers.openai.com/codex/skills">$skill-creator</a>, Anthropic
            publishes an official
            <a href="https://github.com/anthropics/skills/blob/main/skills/skill-creator/SKILL.md">skill-creator</a>
            for turning a workflow into a reusable component.
          </p>
          <p>
            The Agent Skills
            <a href="https://agentskills.io/specification#progressive-disclosure">specification</a>
            recommends keeping <code>SKILL.md</code> small: core instructions only, under 500
            lines and around 5,000 tokens. My rule is to keep the every-run instructions in
            <code>SKILL.md</code>, then move long references, schemas, templates, examples, or
            API details into <code>references/</code> or <code>assets/</code>. The important part
            is telling the agent exactly when to load each file.
          </p>
          <pre class="structure-block"><code>skill-name/
├── SKILL.md       # required: metadata + core instructions
├── scripts/       # optional: repeatable executable helpers
├── references/    # optional: longer docs loaded only when needed
├── assets/        # optional: templates and output resources
└── ...</code></pre>
          <p class="source-note">
            Adapted from the <a href="https://agentskills.io/home#what-are-agent-skills">Agent Skills Overview</a>.
          </p>
          <h4>Add what the agent lacks</h4>
          <p>
            A good skill should spend its tokens on the parts the agent would otherwise get wrong.
            PDF extraction is a simple example. The agent already knows what a PDF is, but it may
            still choose a weak path: read the file directly, lose page boundaries, miss tables, or
            treat a scanned PDF as if it had embedded text.
          </p>
          <p>
            The useful skill content is the operational choice: use <code>pdfplumber</code> for
            text-based PDFs, preserve page markers for later citations, and fall back to OCR with
            <code>pdf2image</code> and <code>pytesseract</code> only when the document is scanned
            or extraction is sparse. That is the kind of instruction the model benefits from.
          </p>
          <h4>Match defaults to risk</h4>
          <p>
            Writing a skill has the same ambiguity problem as prompting: too many equal-looking
            options make the agent slower and less consistent. Pick a default path, then tighten
            the instructions only when the risk requires it. For PDF extraction, the useful default
            is "use <code>pdfplumber</code> for text PDFs; use OCR only for scanned PDFs." For a
            database migration, the skill should give the exact command and sequence because the
            operation is fragile and order-dependent.
          </p>
          <h4>Start specific, then generalize</h4>
          <p>
            I slightly reinterpret the advice to favor procedures over declarations. I would start
            by writing down the specific task that actually worked, then generalize it into a
            reusable procedure. The raw material should be concrete; the final skill should teach
            the agent an approach that survives new inputs.
          </p>
          <h4>Gotchas prevent repeated failures</h4>
          <p>
            A gotchas section is where past failures become future guardrails. These should be
            concrete edge cases the agent has already missed: soft deletes, inconsistent IDs across
            services, misleading health checks, repo-specific validation rules, or any convention
            that breaks reasonable assumptions. If the trigger is non-obvious, keep the gotcha in
            <code>SKILL.md</code> so the agent sees it before making the same mistake again.
          </p>
          <h4>Templates become interfaces</h4>
          <p>
            Templates are useful beyond formatting. They tell the model what shape the work should
            take, and structured output can become input for another function, workflow, or skill.
            Short templates can live inline; longer or conditional templates belong in
            <code>assets/</code> and should be loaded only when needed.
          </p>
          <h4>Optimizing descriptions</h4>
          <p>
            The <code>name</code> and <code>description</code> fields, written in YAML
            frontmatter, matter more than they look. Progressive disclosure means the agent starts
            a session with only those small metadata fields, then loads the full skill body only
            when the task matches. A precise description is the routing layer.
          </p>
          <p>
            The
            <a href="https://agentskills.io/skill-creation/optimizing-descriptions">description optimization guide</a>
            is basically evaluation-driven development for triggering. Build prompts that should
            trigger the skill and near-miss prompts that should not. Run them, observe trigger
            rates, then improve the description instead of guessing.
          </p>
          <h4>Evaluating skills</h4>
          <p>
            The same loop applies to
            <a href="https://agentskills.io/skill-creation/evaluating-skills">skill output quality</a>:
            run the task with the skill, compare it against a baseline or expected result, then
            update the description, instructions, gotchas, scripts, or templates. A planning skill
            like <a href={`${base}components/skills/grill-me/`}>Grill Me</a> can help generate
            realistic test scenarios before the agent runs the evals.
          </p>
          <h4>Using scripts</h4>
          <p>
            Skills can also bundle scripts when the work should be repeatable instead of rewritten
            every time. For one-off Python tools, <code>uvx</code> can run packages in isolated
            environments. For bundled Python scripts, <code>uv run</code> can execute a script with
            inline dependencies, which keeps the skill self-contained and easier for the agent to
            use correctly.
          </p>
          <h3>My own thoughts</h3>
          <h4>Reuse is the point</h4>
          <p>
            The useful move is reuse. When I notice repeated work, I would ask the agent to turn
            that workflow into a skill, then use the skill again as a review pass, implementation
            checklist, or repo-wide audit.
          </p>
          <h4>A skill has its own SDLC</h4>
          <p>
            I should treat skill creation as a small software lifecycle, not a one-time prompt
            rewrite. The flow starts when real work exposes a repeated workflow, a repeated agent
            correction, or a reusable review checklist.
          </p>
          <div class="sdlc-diagram" aria-label="Skill SDLC diagram">
            <div class="sdlc-main-flow">
              <article class="sdlc-node">
                <span class="sdlc-kicker">01 Component</span>
                <strong>Discover from real work</strong>
                <p>
                  Start from an actual task. Capture the steps that worked, corrections I gave the
                  agent, input/output shape, and repo-specific constraints.
                </p>
              </article>
              <article class="sdlc-node">
                <span class="sdlc-kicker">02 Component</span>
                <strong>Draft with a skill creator</strong>
                <p>
                  Turn concrete examples into a reusable procedure. Decide where the agent gets
                  freedom and where exact commands, order, or validation gates are required.
                </p>
              </article>
              <article class="sdlc-node">
                <span class="sdlc-kicker">03 Component</span>
                <strong>Package resources</strong>
                <p>
                  Keep <code>SKILL.md</code> focused. Add <code>references/</code> for domain
                  detail, <code>scripts/</code> for deterministic checks, and
                  <code>assets/</code> for templates or reusable output shapes.
                </p>
              </article>
              <article class="sdlc-node">
                <span class="sdlc-kicker">04 Gate</span>
                <strong>Test by running it</strong>
                <p>
                  Run the skill a few times on realistic tasks. Read the execution trace, not just
                  the final answer. Simple skills may stop here and move into regular use.
                </p>
              </article>
            </div>

            <div class="sdlc-branch">
              <div class="sdlc-branch-label">Complex or failure-prone skill branch</div>
              <div class="sdlc-branch-grid">
                <article class="sdlc-node sdlc-node-compact">
                  <strong>Isolate the testbed</strong>
                  <p>Use a fresh repo, fixture workspace, or worktree so the eval starts clean.</p>
                </article>
                <article class="sdlc-node sdlc-node-compact">
                  <strong>Run eval cases</strong>
                  <p>
                    Include should-trigger prompts, near-misses, normal cases, edge cases, and one
                    messy realistic case with paths or partial context.
                  </p>
                </article>
                <article class="sdlc-node sdlc-node-compact">
                  <strong>Compare and grade</strong>
                  <p>
                    Compare with-skill vs without-skill, or new skill vs old snapshot. Inspect
                    artifacts, assertions, timing, and failure traces.
                  </p>
                </article>
              </div>
            </div>

            <div class="sdlc-feedback">
              <strong>Feedback loop</strong>
              <ul class="sdlc-feedback-list">
                <li>No trigger means revise the description.</li>
                <li>Wrong path means add a <code>SKILL.md</code> gotcha.</li>
                <li>Mechanical rule means add or improve a script.</li>
                <li>Weak output shape means add a template.</li>
              </ul>
              <p>Every failure should come back as a sharper component.</p>
            </div>
          </div>
          <h4>Good starting points</h4>
          <p>
            Some skills are simple and worth starting on immediately; others are complex enough to
            deserve scripts, templates, and evals. Either way, the point is the same: package the
            repeatable parts so the agent saves time and attention, and we can spend more energy on
            the work we actually enjoy. The two easiest categories to start with are domain
            expertise and repeated workflows.
          </p>
          <h4>Domain expertise becomes reusable</h4>
          <p>
            Public skills are usually a starting point. They rarely match the shape of my
            codebase perfectly, because the valuable part often comes from a specific engineering
            observation.
          </p>
          <ul class="takeaway-list">
            <li>
              <strong>Async call chains.</strong>
              In Python projects, an agent may add <code>asyncio.gather</code> around one layer of
              API calls, while the next layer still awaits requests one by one. The code looks
              async, but concurrency does not propagate through the call stack, so performance
              quietly suffers.
            </li>
            <li>
              <strong>Money and validation.</strong>
              A PR may define a Pydantic model and still use <code>float</code> for an amount at
              the API boundary. In banking or payments code, monetary values should be represented
              with <code>Decimal</code> and validated consistently at the boundary because binary
              floats cannot represent most decimal fractions exactly. This is the kind of domain
              convention worth encoding into a Python safety check.
            </li>
          </ul>
          <p>
            That safety check can include team-agreed conventions: no <code>float</code> for
            money, explicit <code>Decimal</code> handling for amount fields, async code that
            preserves concurrency across nested calls, and whatever patterns the repo has learned
            the hard way. Once those observations are explicit, a useful team-specific skill
            exists: run it as a review pass and let the agent audit the repo with that lens.
          </p>
          <h4>Repeated workflows become reusable</h4>
          <p>
            The same idea applies to GitHub work, where the skills integration is especially
            strong. Actions, deploys, release flows, and other multi-step workflows across
            multiple repos are good candidates for skills. Instead of triggering one workflow in
            repo A, waiting for it, clicking the next one in repo B, and losing focus while
            switching context, making a skill for the sequence can help you focus on the task that
            actually deserves your attention. "Attention is all you need" applies to engineers
            during development too.
          </p>
          <p>
            <strong>The most important thing here for engineers is developing the mindset.</strong>
            When you see repeated work or a workflow that depends on domain expertise, you should
            start thinking about how to package it as a skill.
          </p>
        </section>

        <footer class="next-link">
          <a href={`${base}agentic-coding/skills/verified/`}>
            <span>Next</span>
            <strong>Verified Skills</strong>
            <small>Skills I have tested or turned into working components.</small>
          </a>
        </footer>
      </article>

    </div>
  </section>
</BaseLayout>
